---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="How to work in Figma">

  <section class="guide-intro">
    <p class="guide-eyebrow">For the Myprotein design team</p>
    <h1 class="guide-h1">How to work in Figma</h1>
    <p class="guide-lead">
      The reason designs come back slightly wrong from engineering is rarely that anyone made
      a mistake — it's that Figma files can look perfect on screen while quietly containing
      values that don't match the design system. Spacing eyeballed to 14px instead of
      <code>sp-3</code> (12px). A font that looks medium weight but is technically regular.
      A button colour that's close to primary but is actually a one-off hex.
    </p>
    <p class="guide-lead">
      Engineers — and AI tools — ship what the file says, not what you meant. So the way we
      build in Figma directly affects what gets built.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 1 ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Use variables for colour, spacing, and corner radius</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      When a colour or spacing value isn't connected to a variable, it becomes invisible to
      anyone reading the file — it's just a number. Engineers can't tell if 14px is intentional
      or a rounding error. They can't tell if that teal is primary or a one-off.
    </p>
    <p class="guide-body">
      This matters most for spacing. The most common handoff error on the team is gaps and
      padding coming back wrong — and it's almost always because spacing was set by eye rather
      than pulled from <code>sp-</code> tokens.
    </p>
    <div class="takeaway">
      <p class="takeaway-label">What to do instead</p>
      <p>
        Whenever you apply a colour fill, a gap, padding, or a corner radius, use a variable
        from the design system — they're in the right panel under variables. If the value you
        need isn't there, flag it. Don't hardcode a workaround.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 2 ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Use text styles for typography</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      Font size and weight are the second most common thing to drift in builds. A
      <code>text-base/Medium</code> applied as a text style travels perfectly into a build.
      A 16px Inter Medium set manually looks identical on screen — but it has no name, no
      system connection, and nothing stopping it from being interpreted as Regular.
    </p>
    <div class="takeaway">
      <p class="takeaway-label">What to do instead</p>
      <p>
        Every piece of text in a design should have a named text style applied from the right
        panel. Label, heading, body copy — apply the style. Don't set type properties manually.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 3 ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Don't copy frames, use components</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      When you need a button or a card that already exists somewhere in the file, it's tempting
      to copy and paste the frame. The problem is that a copied frame and the original are now
      completely unrelated — change one, the other stays put.
    </p>
    <p class="guide-body">
      More importantly for handoff, a copied frame no longer carries any information about what
      component it is. As far as the file is concerned, it's just shapes.
    </p>
    <div class="takeaway">
      <p class="takeaway-label">What to do instead</p>
      <p>
        Use instances. Find the component in the assets panel and drag it in, or right-click
        an existing instance and duplicate it. If you need a variation that doesn't exist yet,
        raise it — don't detach and customise a one-off.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 4 ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Auto-layout instead of fixed frames</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      Fixed frames with elements positioned by eye look fine until the content changes — then
      everything overlaps or gaps appear. Auto-layout is also how spacing intent gets
      communicated to engineers: a gap of <code>sp-4</code> set in auto-layout is explicit and
      unambiguous. An element sitting 16px from another one by chance is just that — a chance.
    </p>
    <div class="takeaway">
      <p class="takeaway-label">What to do instead</p>
      <p>
        Build components and layout sections with auto-layout from the start. Set gaps and
        padding using spacing variables, not manual nudges. If you're ever lining things up
        with the arrow keys, that's a signal to use auto-layout instead.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 5 ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Name your layers</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      This one's less about handoff accuracy and more about working well together.
      <em>Frame 47</em> and <em>Group 23</em> make it hard for anyone else — or your future
      self — to navigate a file. It also makes it harder for AI tools to help, since layer
      names are how they understand structure.
    </p>
    <div class="takeaway">
      <p class="takeaway-label">What to do instead</p>
      <p>
        Name frames and groups for what they are — <code>ProductCard</code>,
        <code>SizeSelector</code>, <code>Nav/Mobile</code>. You don't need to name every single
        layer, but anything that represents a real UI element or section should have a
        meaningful name. Use <code>/</code> to show hierarchy: <code>Button/Primary</code>,
        <code>Modal/AddToCart</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Closing ────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-closing">
    <p>
      The point isn't perfection — it's consistency. A file built on variables, text styles,
      and real components doesn't just hand off better, it's also faster to work with and
      easier for the whole team to pick up. These habits take about a week to feel natural,
      and after that you'll wonder why you ever worked any other way.
    </p>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .guide-intro { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .guide-eyebrow {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.5;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .guide-h1 {
    font-size: clamp(28px, 5vw, 40px);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    line-height: 1.15;
  }
  .guide-lead {
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    max-width: 680px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .guide-lead:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  .guide-section {
    margin-bottom: 44px;
    max-width: 680px;
  }
  .section-heading {
    font-size: 20px;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 14px;
    line-height: 1.3;
  }
  .guide-body {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }
  .guide-body:last-of-type { margin-bottom: 16px; }

  .takeaway {
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-mint);
    border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
    padding: 14px 18px;
  }
  .takeaway-label {
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 800;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.55;
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .takeaway p:not(.takeaway-label) {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }

  code {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    padding: 1px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  .takeaway code {
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);
  }

  .guide-closing {
    max-width: 680px;
    margin-top: 56px;
    padding-top: 28px;
    border-top: 2px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .guide-closing p {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .guide-h1 { font-size: 28px; }
    .section-heading { font-size: 18px; }
  }
</style>
